https://laravel.com/docs/6.x/authentication#included-authenticating

&gt; **Path Customization**

&gt; When a user is successfully authenticated, they will be redirected to the /home URI. You can customize the post-authentication redirect location by defining a `redirectTo` property on the `LoginController`, `RegisterController`, `ResetPasswordController`, and `VerificationController`.

&gt; If the redirect path needs custom generation logic you may define a `redirectTo` method instead of a `redirectTo` property:

&gt;     protected function redirectTo()
    {
        return &#39;/path&#39;;
    }

It&#39;s in this `redirectTo` function you can determine which path to send the user to, based on their roles.

You can modify your routes to use different controllers for different roles:

    Route::middleware(&quot;auth&quot;)-&gt;get(&quot;/home&quot;, function(){
        $user = \Auth::user();
        if ($user-&gt;hasRole(&quot;admin&quot;)) {
            return app()
                -&gt;make(\App\Http\Controllers\AdminDashboardController::class)
                -&gt;callAction(&quot;index&quot;, []);
        } else {
            return app()
                -&gt;make(\App\Http\Controllers\UserDashboardController::class)
                -&gt;callAction(&quot;index&quot;, []);
        }
    });

**Note**: The previous answer I&#39;ve written wasn&#39;t working because Laravel stores the routes by their URL&#39;s and doesn&#39;t care about the middleware or group, therefore the latter always overwrites the previous one.

